      <h2 class="teal">What does this mean to me?</h2><br>

      <p>With all the talk about gun violence and gun control controversy, it can be difficult to figure out what one&rsquo;s own views are. Here are some questions you should ask yourself:</p><br>
      
      <ul>
         <li>Under what circumstances do I feel safe?&nbsp;Do I feel safe when I can protect myself from potential enemies, or do I feel more safe when it is less likely that my enemies would be able to obtain the guns required to hurt me from a distance in the first place?</li>
         <li>If you are potentially interested in owning a gun, why do you want to own one?&nbsp;Do you want to own a gun so that you can protect yourself from people? To hunt? To kill people who walk onto your property?</li>
         <li>If citizens can own guns, should they be allowed to carry them in public?&nbsp;Certain states have open carry laws, where people can just bring their guns with them almost wherever they want. Other states prohibit this for safety reasons.</li>
         <li>If citizens can own guns, would I trust someone who owns a gun and has not gone through a background check?&nbsp;Many states do not require background checks, and someone can just walk into a gun store and purchase a gun or ammunition whenever they want.</li>
         <li>Do I trust the intentions of someone who owns a gun?</li>
         <li>Are there any other reasons that someone might want to own a gun besides for reasons that directly or indirectly involve killing people or animals?</li>
         <li>Who is the real root of the problem here?&nbsp;Should we be criticizing citizens who want to own guns for various reasons? Should we blame those who want to prevent others from practicing their Second Amendment right? Should we be attacking the countless gun manufacturing companies that put guns and their ammunition into the product market in the first place? Should we blame no one and accept the status quo of hundreds of mass shootings occurring in America per year? </li>
      </ul><br>

